ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, MnO2 nanosheets (MnO2 NSs) were utilized as a dual signal source to realize the BChE assay based on filter membrane-assisted separation via smartphone RGB and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometer (ICP-MS) analysis. The principle of this method is on the strength that BChE can hydrolyze acetylthiocholine (ATCh) into thiocholine (TCh), which can dissociate MnO2 NSs to Mn2+. After selective separation of MnO2 NSs and Mn2+ by the filter, RGB analysis was proposed to detect the color change of the membrane with a smartphone, while Mn2+ in the filtrate was measured via ICP-MS (
                     Scheme 1
                     ). According to the fact that the filter can assist separate and preconcentrate MnO2 NSs from complex solution to the solid membrane, the observed color was strengthened, while the interference from the substrate can be significantly reduced. The limits of detection (LODs) of 1.3 U/L and 0.001 U/L have been established using smartphone-based RGB and ICP-MS analysis, respectively. Finally, we extended this sensing platform to quantify test of the 40 clinical samples. All test results in dual-mode were in accordance with clinical diagnostic assays, denoting that the activity variation in liver disease patients could be accurately observed. We also used the parathion as the example to assess the screening BChE inhibitor ability of this method.
